<Link id="l00050" /><CodeLine lineNumber="50"><Highlight kind="comment">    /// This is a dependence on the specified instruction which clobbers the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00051" /><CodeLine lineNumber="51"><Highlight kind="comment">    /// desired value.  The pointer member of the MemDepResult pair holds the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00052" /><CodeLine lineNumber="52"><Highlight kind="comment">    /// instruction that clobbers the memory.  For example, this occurs when we</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00053" /><CodeLine lineNumber="53"><Highlight kind="comment">    /// see a may-aliased store to the memory location we care about.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00054" /><CodeLine lineNumber="54"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00055" /><CodeLine lineNumber="55"><Highlight kind="comment">    /// There are several cases that may be interesting here:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00056" /><CodeLine lineNumber="56"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///   1 Loads are clobbered by may-alias stores.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00057" /><CodeLine lineNumber="57"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///   2 Loads are considered clobbered by partially-aliased loads.  The</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00058" /><CodeLine lineNumber="58"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      client may choose to analyze deeper into these cases.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00059" /><CodeLine lineNumber="59"><Highlight kind="normal">    Clobber,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00060" /><CodeLine lineNumber="60"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00061" /><CodeLine lineNumber="61"><Highlight kind="comment">    /// This is a dependence on the specified instruction which defines or</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00062" /><CodeLine lineNumber="62"><Highlight kind="comment">    /// produces the desired memory location.  The pointer member of the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00063" /><CodeLine lineNumber="63"><Highlight kind="comment">    /// MemDepResult pair holds the instruction that defines the memory.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00064" /><CodeLine lineNumber="64"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00065" /><CodeLine lineNumber="65"><Highlight kind="comment">    /// Cases of interest:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00066" /><CodeLine lineNumber="66"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///   1 This could be a load or store for dependence queries on</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00067" /><CodeLine lineNumber="67"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      load/store.  The value loaded or stored is the produced value.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00068" /><CodeLine lineNumber="68"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      Note that the pointer operand may be different than that of the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00069" /><CodeLine lineNumber="69"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      queried pointer due to must aliases and phi translation. Note</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00070" /><CodeLine lineNumber="70"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      that the def may not be the same type as the query, the pointers</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00071" /><CodeLine lineNumber="71"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      may just be must aliases.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00072" /><CodeLine lineNumber="72"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///   2 For loads and stores, this could be an allocation instruction. In</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00073" /><CodeLine lineNumber="73"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      this case, the load is loading an undef value or a store is the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00074" /><CodeLine lineNumber="74"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      first store to (that part of) the allocation.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00075" /><CodeLine lineNumber="75"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///   3 Dependence queries on calls return Def only when they are readonly</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00076" /><CodeLine lineNumber="76"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      calls or memory use intrinsics with identical callees and no</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00077" /><CodeLine lineNumber="77"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      intervening clobbers.  No validation is done that the operands to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00078" /><CodeLine lineNumber="78"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      the calls are the same.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00079" /><CodeLine lineNumber="79"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///   4 For loads and stores, this could be a select instruction that</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00080" /><CodeLine lineNumber="80"><Highlight kind="comment">    ///      defines pointer to this memory location. In this case, users can</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00259" /><CodeLine lineNumber="259"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Provides a lazy, caching interface for making common memory aliasing</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00260" /><CodeLine lineNumber="260"><Highlight kind="comment">/// information queries, backed by LLVM&#39;s alias analysis passes.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00261" /><CodeLine lineNumber="261"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00262" /><CodeLine lineNumber="262"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The dependency information returned is somewhat unusual, but is pragmatic.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00263" /><CodeLine lineNumber="263"><Highlight kind="comment">/// If queried about a store or call that might modify memory, the analysis</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00264" /><CodeLine lineNumber="264"><Highlight kind="comment">/// will return the instruction&#91;s&#93; that may either load from that memory or</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00265" /><CodeLine lineNumber="265"><Highlight kind="comment">/// store to it.  If queried with a load or call that can never modify memory,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00266" /><CodeLine lineNumber="266"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the analysis will return calls and stores that might modify the pointer,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00267" /><CodeLine lineNumber="267"><Highlight kind="comment">/// but generally does not return loads unless a) they are volatile, or</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00268" /><CodeLine lineNumber="268"><Highlight kind="comment">/// b) they load from &#42;must-aliased&#42; pointers.  Returning a dependence on</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00269" /><CodeLine lineNumber="269"><Highlight kind="comment">/// must-alias&#39;d pointers instead of all pointers interacts well with the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00270" /><CodeLine lineNumber="270"><Highlight kind="comment">/// internal caching mechanism.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00271" /><CodeLine lineNumber="271" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memorydependenceresults"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/memorydependenceresults/#a2d532144bcebb13e2fbe5db3dee77abf">MemoryDependenceResults</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
